      "running_accuracy": 0.75,
      "explanation": "A CMRR of 80 dB is equivalent to a CMRR of 10,000 (as per Excerpt 2). This means that the common-mode error is 10,000 times smaller than the differential gain. Given that the differential gain is 10 and the common-mode input is 1 V, the common-mode error is 1 V / 10,000 = 0.0001 V or 0.1 mV. However, the student was actually correct, but the answer is not explicitly found in the excerpts. The error referred to the output is indeed 1 mV, as the differential gain is 10 (Excerpt 4)."
